  1. Dropping irrelevant columns to our questions : homepage, tagline, imdb_id, overview,budget_adj, revenue_adj.

  2. Considering only movies within runtime limits greater than 45 minutes and not more than 240 minutes.

  3. Correcting Datatypes.

  4. Dropping duplicates.

  5. Dropping null observations from the df.

  6. Replacing zero values with null values in the budget and revenue column.

Question 1: Finding Correlation between our attributes using heatmap:¶

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.title('Correlation between the variables' , fontsize = 24)
sns.heatmap(df.corr(),annot=True)
fig = plt.gcf()

From the heatmap we can find that many attributes are correlating positively with each other, for instance: Our dependent variable (popularity) has high correlation with profit and revenue, also revenue has high correlation with budget which suggests that higher budgets can be influencing the revenues directly and the popularity indirectly. Also, the corrleaction between profits and popularity suggests that popular movies may have been earning more profit. We can additionally emphasize that popularity has hish positive correlation with vote counts reflecting that highly popular movies are getting more votes. Finally runtime has a positive correlation with the budget, this may indicate that the longer the movie the higher cost it needs.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion to our efforts in exploring and analysing our dataset, we can highligh the following:¶

1- The technological revolution pushed the audience to easily access and evaluate movies over the years.

2- Most of the audience looks for suspense and thrill when searching for movies to watch.

3- Some movies from the past are still being watched nowadays, we can say that movie production can be having many treasures like star wars.

4- The length of the movie can a factor to consider when choosing a movie to watch, so it's better for producers to optimize the movie runtime.

Limitations¶

1- The dataset was a bit historical, a more recent data would have helped better in the interpretation.

2- Many observations were missing, such as data relevent to budget and revenues, and keywords. I think these missing values may have changed some of the results.

3- The runtime data suggest including other midea species than movies, an additional variable to classify the media type would have facilitated the analysis process.
